{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> ὕπτι-ος</b>, α, ον, <br /> <b>laid on one's back,</b> frequently in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Homerus Epicus \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>], especially of one falling <b>backwards,</b> opposed to πρηνής, πολλοὶ δὲ πρηνεῖς τε καὶ ὕπτιοι ἔκπεσον [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 11.179; ὁ δ᾽ ὕ. ἐν κονίῃσι.. πέσε 15.434, compare 4.522, +others, 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Tyrannus” 811; τὸν δ᾽ ὕ. ὦσ᾽ ἀπὸ δουρός 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 16.863; ἄλλοτ᾽ ἐπὶ πλευρὰς κατακείμενος, ἄλλοτε δ᾽ αὖτε ὕ., ἄλλοτε δὲ πρηνής, of Achilles in his grief, 24.11 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; ὕ. ἀποθανέειν to die <b>lying on one's back,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 4.190; ῥέγκει.. ὕ. 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Equites” 104; ὕπτιον καθεύδειν οὐδενὶ βέλτιόν ἐστιν Diocl. fragment 141; κατεκλίνη ὕ. 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Phaedo” 117e, compare 2nd c.AD: Soranus Medicus 2.87, +others, 2nd c.AD: Galenus Medicus 18(2).56, +others; ὑ. ἀνατετραμμένος 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Euthydemus” 278c \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; of a quadruped, ὀρθοῦ ἑστεῶτος.. καὶ ὑπτίου standing upright and <b>lying on its back,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 2.38, compare “Anthologia Graeca” 5.202 (3rd c.BC: Asclepiades Epigrammaticus). \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__II</b></Level2> ὕ. μέρη, in animals, <b>the under parts,</b> i.e. <b>the belly,</b> opposed to τὰ πρανῆ (the upper parts, the back), [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “de Partibus Animalium” 658a16, +others, compare πρανής 11: hence 4th-3rd c.BC: Theophrastus Philosophus “Historia Plantarum” 1.10.2, 3.14.2 uses ὕπτιος\">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>] of the <b>smoother</b> upper surface of leaves, opposed to πρανής of the rougher and under: γαστὴρ ὑ. the belly <b>uppermost,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Cyclops” 326 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; of the hand, ἐκτείνειν τὴν χεῖρ᾽ ὑ. to hold out the hand <b>with the under side uppermost,</b> to hold out <b>the hollow of</b> the hand, so as to receive something, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Ecclesiazusae” 782; τὴν χεῖρα νῦν μὲν ὑ., νῦν δὲ πρηνῆ προτείνας 1st-2nd c.AD: Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus “Timoleon” 11; τῆς χειρὸς ὑ. τὸ μέσον [prev. author] “Crass.” 18; ὑ. ταῖς χερσὶν ὑποδέχεσθαί τι 2nd-3rd c.AD: Philostratus Sophista “Philostrati majoris imagines” 1.6; ἐδέξαντο ὑπτίαις χερσὶ τὸν τῶν πολεμίων στρατόν 6th c.AD: Procopius Caesariensis Historicus “de Bello Gothico” 3.16.19; οὐλὴ καρπῷ δεξιῷ ὑπτίῳ “PLond.” 2.259.81 (1st c.AD)\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; also ὑ. τὰς χεῖρας ἀνατείνειν lift the <b>upturned</b> hands in prayers, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 1st-2nd c.AD: Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus “Comp. Phil.Flam.” 2, compare 2nd-3rd c.AD: Philostratus Sophista “Philostrati majoris imagines” 2.1; ταῖς χερσὶν ὑπτίαις διαλέγεσθαι 1st-2nd c.AD: Dio Chrysostomus Sophista 33.52 \">Refs 1st c.AD+</a>]; ἐξ ὑπτίας νεῖν swim or float <b>on one's back,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Fragmenta” 665, 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 529c. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__III</b></Level2> generally, of anything <b>turned downside up,</b> πάλος ἐξ ὑπτίου 'πήδησεν.. κράνους from the <b>upturned</b> helmet, <b>with the hollow uppermost,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Septem contra Thebas” 459 (compare 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 7.176)\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; παράθες νυν ὑ. αὐτὴν ἐμοί (i.e. τὴν ἀσπίδα) [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Acharnenses” 583, compare “Lys.” 185, 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 7.82 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ἁψῖδος ἥμισυ ὕπτιον a half-wheel <b>with the concave side uppermost,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 4.72 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; but κύλιξ ὑ. a cup <b>with the bottom uppermost,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Lysistrata” 195 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ὑπτίοις σέλμασιν ναυτίλλεται he sails with the benches <b>upside down,</b> i.e. suffers shipwreck, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Antigone” 716; κεῖσθαι ὥσπερ γάμμα ὕ. 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Oeconomicus” 19.9; σχαλίδες [prev. author] “Cyn.” 6.7 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; περιφέρεια κοίλη καὶ ὑ., opposed to πρηνὴς καὶ κυρτή, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Meteorologica” 350a11. \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__III.2</b></Level3> ἐξ ὑπτίας ἀνάπαλιν διανεῖν τὸν λόγον <b>trace</b> the argument <b>backwards</b> from the conclusion, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Phaedrus” 264a, compare 5th c.AD: Hermias Alexandrinus Philosophus “in Platonis Phaedrum scholia” p.187A. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ἐξ ὑπτίας <b>backwards, in reverse order,</b> ἀπὸ τῶν ἐσχάτων ἐπὶ τὰ πρῶτα ἐπανιόντες [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.AD: Damascius Philosophus “de Principiis” 81; ἐξ ὑπτίας χωροῦντες 5th c.AD: Proclus Philosophus “Hypotyposis astronomicarum positionum” 7.57. \">Refs 5th c.AD+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__IV</b></Level2> of land, <b>flat, horizontal,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 2.7, 4th-3rd c.BC: Theophrastus Philosophus “de Causis Plantarum” 5.12.7, 2nd c.AD: Appianus Historicus “Bella Civilia” 4.2, “Mith.” 42, 2nd-3rd c.AD: Aelianus “De Natura Animalium - Ar.Byzantine Epit.” 16.15, 1st-2nd c.AD: Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus 2.193e, 530a; ἐν ὑπτίῳ τοῦ ὄρους 2nd c.AD: Pausanias Periegeta 8.13.1 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ὕ. μᾶλλον ἢ ὄρθιος, of a flight of shallow steps, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd c.AD: Lucianus Sophista “Hipp.” 5 \">Refs 2nd c.AD+</a>]; of the sea, <b>smooth,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd-3rd c.AD: Philostratus Sophista “Philostrati majoris imagines” 2.17, 4th c.AD: Libanius Sophista “Descriptiones” 7.5. \">Refs 2nd c.AD+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__V</b></Level2> <i>metaphorically</i>, <b>supine, lazy, careless,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd c.AD: Aristides Rhetor “Orationes” 31(11).5, [prev. author] 2.112J., 2nd c.AD(?): Pollianus Epigrammaticus 1.158, etc.\">Refs 2nd c.AD+</a>]; ἔστω.. μὴ ὕ. ὁ τράχηλος his neck should not be <b>relaxed,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-3rd c.BC: Zeno Citieus Stoicus 1.58; δεῖ αὐτῷ καὶ αὐχένος ὀρθοῦ καὶ βλέμματος οὐχ ὑπτίου 4th c.AD: Libanius Sophista “Orationes” 64.103; προσφέρομαι τῶν αὐστηρῶν τι.. ὅταν αἴσθωμαί ποθ᾽ ὕ. [τὸν στόμαχον] γεγονότα καὶ πλησίον ἥκοντα ναυτίας 2nd c.AD: Galenus Medicus 6.601 \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>], compare 15.460; of language, <b>flat, tedious,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 1st c.BC: Dionysius Halicarnassensis “de Isocrate” 15, “Din.” 8, 2nd c.AD: Hermogenes Rhetor “περὶ τῶν στάσεων” 3, etc. \">Refs 1st c.BC+</a>] <i>adverb</i>, ὑπτίως ἔχειν to be <b>flat and dull,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 1st c.AD: Philo Judaeus 1.305; ὑ. καὶ οὐ ποιητικῶς ᾖσεν 2nd-3rd c.AD: Philostratus Sophista “Heroicus” 2.19. \">Refs 1st c.AD+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__VI</b></Level2> <b>passive,</b> of Verbs, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 3rd c.AD(?): Diogenes Laertius 7.43, 64 \">Refs 3rd c.AD+</a>]; compare {ὀρθός}","strongNumber":"G9602","accentedUnicode":"ὕπτιος","shortDef":"steep","mediumDef":"steep","stepGloss":"steep","stepTransliteration":"huptios","_step_Type":"word"}]}